  "title": "山核桃大街谋杀案",
  "source_file": "data\\raw\\detectiveqa\\novel_data_en\\121-山核桃大街谋杀案-阿加莎克里斯蒂.txt",
  "chunk_index": 30,
  "summary": "Pat reveals to Nigel that she had replaced the poison in a small bottle with baking soda to make it look identical, hiding the actual poison in her handkerchief drawer for safety. She had intended to return the poison to the hospital via Silvia once Nigel won a bet, but Pat confesses that the poison has disappeared; she noticed it was missing even before Silvia died. Nigel admits that he was the one who originally stole the poison to impress others and expresses fear of being held responsible for Silvia's death.\n\nNigel conducts a frantic search of Pat's room, looking through her clothing and drawers for the \"baking soda.\" During this search, Sally Finch enters the room to borrow a stamp from Pat's desk to mail a letter. Nigel discovers that the letter Pat wrote was actually addressed to his father and, in a fit of intense anger, tears it into pieces.\n\nAs Pat attempts to reconcile Nigel with his father, the renowned chemist Arthur Stanley—who is reported to be in critical condition—Nigel reveals his deep-seated hatred for him. Nigel claims his father murdered his mother by intentionally giving her an overdose of barbiturates so he could marry another woman. Nigel explains that he changed his name and left to avoid his father after revealing he knew the truth, asserting that his father's mistress eventually left him because she discovered his crimes.",
